---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Web Performance Budget Calculator",
  "description": "Calculate and set a performance budget for your website to ensure fast load times and healthy Core Web Vitals.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "siliconbased.dev"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a performance budget?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A performance budget is a set of limits imposed on metrics that affect site performance. This usually takes the form of maximum file sizes (e.g., max 200KB of JavaScript, 500KB of images) to ensure the site remains fast as new features are added."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is JavaScript budgeted differently than images?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Byte for byte, JavaScript is much more expensive than images. An image only needs to be downloaded and decoded. JavaScript must be downloaded, parsed, compiled, and executed on the main thread, which blocks interactivity."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I enforce a performance budget?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You can enforce budgets using CI/CD tools. For example, Lighthouse CI or Webpack performance hints can automatically fail a build or block a pull request if the new code exceeds the defined budget limits."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="siliconbased"
  title="Performance Budget Calculator"
  description="Set a page weight budget and allocate it across HTML, CSS, JS, images, and fonts."
  canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/performance-budget-calculator"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Performance Budget Calculator</h1>
      <p>Set a target page weight and calculate how much you can spend on JavaScript, CSS, Images, and Fonts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <p>A performance budget is a limit you set on the size of your web pages. Without a budget, websites inevitably suffer from "feature creep," becoming bloated and slow over time. This ruins your <a href="/web-performance-guide">Web Performance</a> and Core Web Vitals.</p>

      <h2>Interactive Budget Calculator</h2>
      <p>Enter your target total page weight (in kilobytes) to generate a recommended budget breakdown. A good starting target for a fast mobile experience is <strong>1000 KB (1 MB)</strong>.</p>

      <div class="interactive-tool card">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="totalBudget">Target Total Page Weight (gzipped):</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="totalBudget" min="100" max="5000" step="50" value="1000">
            <span class="unit">KB</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="budget-results">
          <div class="budget-chart">
            <div id="chartHtml" class="chart-segment html-seg" style="width: 5%"></div>
            <div id="chartCss" class="chart-segment css-seg" style="width: 5%"></div>
            <div id="chartJs" class="chart-segment js-seg" style="width: 20%"></div>
            <div id="chartFonts" class="chart-segment fonts-seg" style="width: 10%"></div>
            <div id="chartImages" class="chart-segment images-seg" style="width: 60%"></div>
          </div>

          <div class="budget-grid">
            <div class="budget-item html-item">
              <div class="item-header">
                <span class="color-dot" style="background: #3b82f6"></span>
                <span class="item-name">HTML</span>
              </div>
              <div class="item-val" id="valHtml">50 KB</div>
              <div class="item-pct">5%</div>
            </div>

            <div class="budget-item css-item">
              <div class="item-header">
                <span class="color-dot" style="background: #10b981"></span>
                <span class="item-name">CSS</span>
              </div>
              <div class="item-val" id="valCss">50 KB</div>
              <div class="item-pct">5%</div>
            </div>

            <div class="budget-item js-item">
              <div class="item-header">
                <span class="color-dot" style="background: #f59e0b"></span>
                <span class="item-name">JavaScript</span>
              </div>
              <div class="item-val" id="valJs">200 KB</div>
              <div class="item-pct">20%</div>
            </div>

            <div class="budget-item fonts-item">
              <div class="item-header">
                <span class="color-dot" style="background: #8b5cf6"></span>
                <span class="item-name">Fonts</span>
              </div>
              <div class="item-val" id="valFonts">100 KB</div>
              <div class="item-pct">10%</div>
            </div>

            <div class="budget-item images-item">
              <div class="item-header">
                <span class="color-dot" style="background: #ec4899"></span>
                <span class="item-name">Images/Media</span>
              </div>
              <div class="item-val" id="valImages">600 KB</div>
              <div class="item-pct">60%</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>How the Budget is Calculated</h2>
      <p>The calculator uses standard industry ratios for resource allocation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Images (60%):</strong> Images are visually important but relatively cheap for the browser to process. Most of your budget should go here.</li>
        <li><strong>JavaScript (20%):</strong> JS is the most "expensive" byte on the web because it must be executed. Keeping this budget strict is crucial for interactivity.</li>
        <li><strong>Fonts (10%):</strong> 1-2 optimized, subsetted web fonts usually fit within this budget.</li>
        <li><strong>HTML (5%):</strong> The structure of your page. Should rarely exceed 50KB.</li>
        <li><strong>CSS (5%):</strong> If using modern utility frameworks or critical CSS, 50-100KB is plenty.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Enforcing the Budget</h2>
      <p>A budget is useless if it isn't enforced. You should integrate performance budgeting directly into your CI/CD pipeline.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Lighthouse CI</h3>
        <p>You can configure Lighthouse CI to fail your build if certain budgets are exceeded:</p>
        <pre><code>// lighthouserc.json
&#123;
  "ci": &#123;
    "assert": &#123;
      "budgetsFile": "budget.json"
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
        <pre><code>// budget.json
[
  &#123;
    "resourceSizes": [
      &#123; "resourceType": "script", "budget": 200 &#125;,
      &#123; "resourceType": "image", "budget": 600 &#125;
    ]
  &#125;
]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Webpack Performance Hints</h3>
        <p>If you use Webpack, you can set it to throw warnings or errors during the build process:</p>
        <pre><code>// webpack.config.js
module.exports = &#123;
  // ...
  performance: &#123;
    hints: "warning", // or "error"
    maxEntrypointSize: 250000, // 250kb
    maxAssetSize: 250000
  &#125;
&#125;;</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is a performance budget?</h3>
          <p>A performance budget is a set of limits imposed on metrics that affect site performance. This usually takes the form of maximum file sizes (e.g., max 200KB of JavaScript, 500KB of images) to ensure the site remains fast as new features are added.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why is JavaScript budgeted differently than images?</h3>
          <p>Byte for byte, JavaScript is much more expensive than images. An image only needs to be downloaded and decoded. JavaScript must be downloaded, parsed, compiled, and executed on the main thread, which blocks interactivity and drains battery life.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I enforce a performance budget?</h3>
          <p>You can enforce budgets using CI/CD tools. For example, Lighthouse CI or Webpack performance hints can automatically fail a build or block a pull request if the new code exceeds the defined budget limits.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const input = document.getElementById('totalBudget');

      const valHtml = document.getElementById('valHtml');
      const valCss = document.getElementById('valCss');
      const valJs = document.getElementById('valJs');
      const valFonts = document.getElementById('valFonts');
      const valImages = document.getElementById('valImages');

      // Fixed Ratios
      const ratios = {
        html: 0.05,
        css: 0.05,
        js: 0.20,
        fonts: 0.10,
        images: 0.60
      };

      function updateBudget() {
        const total = parseFloat(input.value);
        if (isNaN(total) || total < 0) return;

        valHtml.textContent = Math.round(total * ratios.html) + ' KB';
        valCss.textContent = Math.round(total * ratios.css) + ' KB';
        valJs.textContent = Math.round(total * ratios.js) + ' KB';
        valFonts.textContent = Math.round(total * ratios.fonts) + ' KB';
        valImages.textContent = Math.round(total * ratios.images) + ' KB';
      }

      input.addEventListener('input', updateBudget);
      updateBudget(); // init
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #fff; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .content h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #fff; }
    .content h3 { font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #fff; }
    .content p { line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #d1d5db; }
    .content ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: #d1d5db; line-height: 1.7; }
    .content li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }

    .content a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
    .content a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    pre { background: #0f172a; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; overflow-x: auto; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    code { font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Monaco, Consolas, monospace; font-size: 0.9em; color: #e2e8f0; }
    p code, li code { background: #1e293b; padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 4px; }

    /* Interactive Tool */
    .interactive-tool { margin: 2rem 0; padding: 2rem; }
    .input-group { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; max-width: 350px; margin: 0 auto 2.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .input-group label { font-weight: 600; color: #fff; }
    .input-wrapper { display: flex; align-items: center; background: #0f172a; border: 2px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden; transition: border-color 0.2s; }
    .input-wrapper:focus-within { border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    .input-wrapper input { flex: 1; padding: 1rem; background: transparent; border: none; color: #fff; font-size: 1.4rem; font-family: monospace; outline: none; text-align: center; font-weight: bold; }
    .input-wrapper .unit { padding: 0 1rem; color: #94a3b8; font-weight: 600; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05); height: 100%; display: flex; align-items: center; border-left: 1px solid var(--border-color); }

    .budget-chart { display: flex; height: 24px; border-radius: 12px; overflow: hidden; margin-bottom: 2rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .chart-segment { height: 100%; }
    .html-seg { background: #3b82f6; }
    .css-seg { background: #10b981; }
    .js-seg { background: #f59e0b; }
    .fonts-seg { background: #8b5cf6; }
    .images-seg { background: #ec4899; }

    .budget-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(140px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; }
    .budget-item { background: #0f172a; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; }
    .item-header { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
    .color-dot { width: 12px; height: 12px; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; }
    .item-name { font-weight: 600; color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; }
    .item-val { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; font-family: monospace; }
    .item-pct { font-size: 0.8rem; color: #64748b; margin-top: 0.2rem; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-item { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .faq-item h3 { font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; margin-top: 0; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>